gs":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name probably from an unidentified place in Normandy named with Old French <i>crues</i>, <i>crus</i>, <i>creus</i> ‘hollow’. Creuse (in Somme, Picardy) and Cruys-Straëte (formerly in Flanders, now in the French département of Nord), which have the same etymology, are alternative possibilities but seem less likely on geographical and tenurial grounds.","English: perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>crus(e)</i> ‘bold, fierce’, although the regular development would be to <i>Crowse</i> (rhyming with <i>house</i>).","North German: variant of   Krause  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomasine","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: A twin; Thomasine is a female version."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":119,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomasine Crese was born in 1430, in Launceston, Cornwall, England, her father, Will Crese, was 16 and her mother, Mrs. William Crese, was 5. She married John Wood VI about 1452, in North Tawton, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in North Tawton, Devon, England."},"et":{"1430–":"1430–Surnud","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1425–1469":"1425–1469","1460–1493":"1460–1493","1462–1522":"1462–1522","1415–Male":"1415–Surnud","1426–Female":"1426–Surnud","1426":"1426","1415":"1415","circa 1452":"umbes 1452","1469":"1469","1425":"1425","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1493":"1493","1549":"1549","North Tawton, Devonshire, England":"North Tawton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Launceston, Cornwall, England":"Launceston, Cornwall, England","North Tawton, Devon, England":"North Tawton, Devon, England","Collingtree, Northamptonshire, England":"Collingtree, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1430–":"1430–Kuollut","1430–Female":"1430–Kuollut","1425–1469":"1425–1469","1460–1493":"1460–1493","1462–1522":"1462–1522","1415–Male":"1415–Kuollut","1426–Female":"1426–Kuollut","1426":"1426","1415":"1415","circa 1452":"noin 1452","1469":"1469","1425":"1425","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1493":"1493","1549":"1549","North Tawton, Devonshire, England":"North Tawton, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Launceston, Cornwall, England":"Launceston, Cornwall, England","North Tawton, Devon, England":"North Tawton, Devon, England","Collingtree, Northamptonshire, England":"Collingtree, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1430–":"1430–Décédée","1430–Female":"1430–Décédée","1425–1469":"1425–1469","1460–1493":"1460–1493","1462–1522":"1462–1522","1415–Male":"1415–Décédé","1426–Female":"1426–Décédée","1426":"1426","1415":"1415","circa 1452":"environ 1452","1469":"1469","1425":"1425","1522":"1522","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1462":"1462","1460":"1460","1493":"1493","1549":"1549","North Tawton, Devonshire, England":"Nor